Reason: Starting from the normal boiling point of octane, which is approximately 126°C, we can analyze the effect of the functional groups present in ethyl octanoate to predict its melting point. Firstly, we can consider the ester group (-COO-). Ester groups normally lower the boiling point compared to the corresponding carboxylic acids because they cannot form hydrogen bonds as effectively with other molecules of the same compound, resulting in weaker intermolecular forces. Esters generally tend to have a lower melting point as well, so this effect in esters can be estimated to lower the melting point by approximately -30°C relative to the parent hydrocarbon. Additionally, the ethyl group (C2H5-) is bulkier than a methyl group and has more surface area, which can increase the van der Waals forces slightly more than a methyl group, but not as much as it would increase the boiling point due to the larger surface area potentially leading to a lower increase in melting point. The influence of an ethyl group on the melting point might be around +5°C compared to methane. Combining these effects, we would expect the ester to have a lower melting point than octane because the negative impact of the ester functional group outweighs the slight positive contribution of the ethyl group.
